<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-208-652  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 208 652.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  April 24 1989 v11 n17 p11(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>View of connectivity is changing: emphasis is shifting away fromplatforms to ways they are linked.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Darrow, Barbara.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Experts speaking at Connect '89 claim that as corporations tiecomputers of varying sizes and makes together, the emphasis isshifting from the platforms to the way in which they are linked.andO;Analyst Larry DeBoever states that in companies with bothmicrocomputers and mainframes, microcomputer users are beginningto view the big computer as another peripheral.andP;  He claims,however, that users' ability to manipulate increasing amounts ofdata with 32-bit microprocessors, multitasking operating systemsand mainframe-size address spaces may turn even the fastestmicro-mainframe links into bottlenecks.andP;  Fiber Distributed DataInterface (FDDI) vendors Fibronics International Inc and ArtelCommunications Corp claim that FDDI networks running at100M-bits-sec is a remedy to this problem.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber Distributed Data Interface StandardConferencesConnectivityNetworksMicro-Mainframe Communication.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>